WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.590 --> 00:00:03.890
PROFESSOR ROBERT SHILLER:
OK, good morning.

00:00:03.890 --> 00:00:09.590
Well, today I want to talk about
what, to me, is a very

00:00:09.590 --> 00:00:13.525
interesting topic, and that
is futures markets.

00:00:16.290 --> 00:00:18.230
Not very interesting
to most people.

00:00:18.230 --> 00:00:21.160
Most people have no idea
what they are.

00:00:21.160 --> 00:00:27.080
But I think that, well, futures
markets, what we're

00:00:27.080 --> 00:00:29.560
really talking about is --

00:00:29.560 --> 00:00:33.240
There are different ways
of viewing it.

00:00:33.240 --> 00:00:38.290
Futures markets for things like
agricultural commodities,

00:00:38.290 --> 00:00:44.770
or interest rates, or financial
securities, are

00:00:44.770 --> 00:00:47.740
markets about the future.

00:00:47.740 --> 00:00:50.550
They're markets that, in some
sense, predict the future.

00:00:53.130 --> 00:00:55.630
And future matters, right?

00:00:55.630 --> 00:00:56.390
We live a life.

00:00:56.390 --> 00:01:00.120
We have a long horizon.

00:01:00.120 --> 00:01:04.090
I said before, I think that your
planning horizon must be

00:01:04.090 --> 00:01:08.280
at least a century, because
you'll probably live that long

00:01:08.280 --> 00:01:10.300
anyway, with modern medicine.

00:01:10.300 --> 00:01:12.240
And you care about other
people, too.

00:01:12.240 --> 00:01:18.330
So, the beauty of futures
markets is that we have prices

00:01:18.330 --> 00:01:20.880
for the future.

00:01:20.880 --> 00:01:23.240
We talked already about
forward markets.

00:01:23.240 --> 00:01:27.570
We talked about forward
interest rates.

00:01:27.570 --> 00:01:33.360
And that is related to what
we're talking about.

00:01:33.360 --> 00:01:38.820
Forwards and futures are
similar concepts.

00:01:38.820 --> 00:01:43.700
Futures is the more
precise concept.

00:01:43.700 --> 00:01:46.090
Or the more developed concept.

00:01:46.090 --> 00:01:49.300
And I'll explain the difference
between forwards

00:01:49.300 --> 00:01:51.480
and futures.

00:01:51.480 --> 00:01:56.560
But just in a nutshell, futures
markets are organized

00:01:56.560 --> 00:02:00.670
markets, like the stock
market, that trade

00:02:00.670 --> 00:02:07.480
standardized contracts,
representing things that will

00:02:07.480 --> 00:02:09.720
happen at future dates.

00:02:09.720 --> 00:02:10.450
And because they're

00:02:10.450 --> 00:02:13.520
standardized, they're worldwide.

00:02:13.520 --> 00:02:16.800
Everybody looks at them
and uses them.

00:02:16.800 --> 00:02:22.950
Whereas forward markets are more
specialized markets that,

00:02:22.950 --> 00:02:26.420
typically, are not as easy
to interpret or as clear.

00:02:29.020 --> 00:02:34.910
So, futures markets are, in some
sense, more fundamental

00:02:34.910 --> 00:02:36.860
and important.

00:02:36.860 --> 00:02:38.630
I have a particular
interest --

00:02:38.630 --> 00:02:41.240
I've been interested in futures
markets myself for

00:02:41.240 --> 00:02:42.550
many years.

00:02:42.550 --> 00:02:44.120
And wondering, why
they're not even

00:02:44.120 --> 00:02:45.890
bigger and more important.

00:02:45.890 --> 00:02:52.330
So, in 1993, I wrote a book
called Macro Markets, about

00:02:52.330 --> 00:02:54.300
let's make our markets
bigger and more

00:02:54.300 --> 00:02:56.610
important, and more pervasive.

00:02:56.610 --> 00:02:59.910
And I've been trying
to do that.

00:02:59.910 --> 00:03:04.820
Notably, in 2006, I was working
with the Chicago

00:03:04.820 --> 00:03:09.540
Mercantile Exchange, which
is the biggest futures

00:03:09.540 --> 00:03:11.150
market in the world.

00:03:11.150 --> 00:03:14.310
And we created home
price futures.

00:03:14.310 --> 00:03:16.405
And they've been trading
now for five years.

00:03:16.405 --> 00:03:19.700
But I'm not really going to talk
about them, because they

00:03:19.700 --> 00:03:21.310
have so far disappointed.

00:03:21.310 --> 00:03:24.590
They're not important,
at least not yet.

00:03:24.590 --> 00:03:25.720
But I'm going to
talk about some

00:03:25.720 --> 00:03:28.105
important futures markets.

00:03:36.400 --> 00:03:42.980
First, I want to put just a
couple of definitions up.

00:03:42.980 --> 00:03:46.590
Futures, that's what we're going
to talk about most in

00:03:46.590 --> 00:03:50.550
this lecture, and it has a
special meaning in finance.

00:03:50.550 --> 00:03:53.445
And I was contrasting
that to forwards.

00:04:04.160 --> 00:04:08.605
But both of these together
are derivatives.

00:04:13.920 --> 00:04:20.360
And that means that the price in
these markets derives from

00:04:20.360 --> 00:04:24.580
a price in some other market.

00:04:24.580 --> 00:04:34.460
There's a primary or underlying
market, which has

00:04:34.460 --> 00:04:35.630
its own price.

00:04:35.630 --> 00:04:39.280
And then there's a derivative
market that has a futures

00:04:39.280 --> 00:04:40.850
price or a forward price.

00:04:43.610 --> 00:04:51.090
I guess I'm speaking in kind of
abstract terms. Well, let

00:04:51.090 --> 00:04:52.810
me just start --

00:04:52.810 --> 00:04:54.910
I want to give you an example,
and we'll see better what I'm

00:04:54.910 --> 00:04:55.810
talking about.

00:04:55.810 --> 00:04:58.950
But let me just first comment
just on this word,

00:04:58.950 --> 00:05:01.410
derivatives.

00:05:01.410 --> 00:05:06.120
To people in finance,
derivatives are an exciting

00:05:06.120 --> 00:05:08.580
development of financial
markets.

00:05:08.580 --> 00:05:11.120
We start out with a simple
market and we develop

00:05:11.120 --> 00:05:15.610
derivative markets, that add
more detail and information

00:05:15.610 --> 00:05:18.550
than was in the underlying
or primary market.

00:05:21.260 --> 00:05:22.510
That's exciting.

00:05:22.510 --> 00:05:24.020
I find it exciting.

00:05:24.020 --> 00:05:24.455
However --

00:05:24.455 --> 00:05:28.390
I don't know how often you hear
this word, derivative --

00:05:28.390 --> 00:05:30.650
it's become a four-letter
word.

00:05:30.650 --> 00:05:35.670
It's become an ugly word.

00:05:35.670 --> 00:05:37.220
Why is that?

00:05:37.220 --> 00:05:40.030
I think it's, because people
blame the current financial

00:05:40.030 --> 00:05:43.240
crisis on derivatives, whether
rightly or wrongly.

00:05:46.960 --> 00:05:54.030
And it's because, I think,
there's a public anger about

00:05:54.030 --> 00:05:57.560
derivatives that is largely
due to misunderstanding.

00:06:01.350 --> 00:06:05.610
I mentioned before that I think
that finance tends to

00:06:05.610 --> 00:06:08.370
attract sociopaths.

00:06:08.370 --> 00:06:10.190
I mentioned that, I defined
that for you.

00:06:10.190 --> 00:06:14.960
People who want to manipulate,
and fool, and deceive people.

00:06:14.960 --> 00:06:17.030
But I don't think the financial
community is

00:06:17.030 --> 00:06:21.200
particularly populated
by sociopaths.

00:06:21.200 --> 00:06:23.850
You might think so, reading
some accounts.

00:06:23.850 --> 00:06:26.460
But I think, it's not true.

00:06:26.460 --> 00:06:29.580
And I think, it's not true,
because the financial

00:06:29.580 --> 00:06:32.460
community knows about
this problem

00:06:32.460 --> 00:06:35.350
and ejects such people.

00:06:35.350 --> 00:06:36.460
They get caught.

00:06:36.460 --> 00:06:40.590
And you can't make a career in
finance if you're a sociopath.

00:06:40.590 --> 00:06:43.930
So, if you think you have this
problem, that you have

00:06:43.930 --> 00:06:47.950
sociopathic tendencies, I would
advise you not to go

00:06:47.950 --> 00:06:51.440
into finance, because you will
get caught and ejected.

00:06:51.440 --> 00:06:54.230
So, save yourself the trouble.

00:06:54.230 --> 00:06:56.130
Don't go into finance.

00:06:56.130 --> 00:06:58.910
Pick some field where you
can't hurt anybody.

00:06:58.910 --> 00:07:03.010
And that would be a smart
thing to do, if

00:07:03.010 --> 00:07:05.980
you have such a problem.

00:07:05.980 --> 00:07:11.790
So, I think we need to regulate
derivatives markets,

00:07:11.790 --> 00:07:13.220
and that's what I'm
talking about.

00:07:13.220 --> 00:07:16.640
And we need self-regulation of
the markets themselves, but we

00:07:16.640 --> 00:07:19.120
need government regulation
as well.

00:07:19.120 --> 00:07:21.660
But there's nothing evil
about derivatives.

00:07:21.660 --> 00:07:27.290
And in fact, derivatives are
fundamental to the way I think

00:07:27.290 --> 00:07:29.350
a modern economy works.

00:07:29.350 --> 00:07:32.690
So, I had you read
an article --

00:07:32.690 --> 00:07:35.390
I put it on an earlier section
of the reading list --

00:07:35.390 --> 00:07:47.765
by Charles Conant, who wrote
a book in 1904 called Wall

00:07:47.765 --> 00:07:49.350
Street and the Country.

00:07:49.350 --> 00:07:52.040
And you should have
read that by how.

00:07:52.040 --> 00:07:56.540
He starts out by saying, it's
just amazing, how public

00:07:56.540 --> 00:08:01.660
opinion thinks that speculation
is evil.

00:08:01.660 --> 00:08:05.690
And they don't understand that
speculation is just business.

00:08:05.690 --> 00:08:08.500
I mean, business decisions
involve

00:08:08.500 --> 00:08:10.460
guesses about the future.

00:08:10.460 --> 00:08:14.040
And so, when you have
well-developed markets, these

00:08:14.040 --> 00:08:16.640
guesses become market prices.

00:08:16.640 --> 00:08:23.849
And so, the prices go into
the calculations

00:08:23.849 --> 00:08:25.150
that everyone makes.

00:08:25.150 --> 00:08:28.680
And the calculations are
just done better.

00:08:28.680 --> 00:08:31.330
Somehow, there's just a failure
for most people to

00:08:31.330 --> 00:08:32.580
understand it.

00:08:35.050 --> 00:08:40.890
And I'm hoping in this lecture
to try to give some more

00:08:40.890 --> 00:08:44.440
understanding of
these markets.

00:08:44.440 --> 00:08:45.800
I think they're fascinating.

00:08:45.800 --> 00:08:48.350
Most people apparently don't,
because you don't hear them

00:08:48.350 --> 00:08:49.600
brought up very much.

00:08:52.290 --> 00:08:56.200
I want to just say a little
bit more about hostility

00:08:56.200 --> 00:09:03.000
toward derivative markets
and futures markets, and

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:05.870
speculation in general.

00:09:05.870 --> 00:09:10.360
In 1991, that was 20 years
ago, I wrote a joint

00:09:10.360 --> 00:09:11.940
paper with a --

00:09:11.940 --> 00:09:13.850
I don't remember whether
I mentioned this,

00:09:13.850 --> 00:09:15.160
probably not --

00:09:15.160 --> 00:09:19.570
with a Russian, a young man from
Russia that I met when I

00:09:19.570 --> 00:09:23.380
was visiting the Soviet Union,
just before the end of the

00:09:23.380 --> 00:09:24.600
Soviet Union.

00:09:24.600 --> 00:09:29.690
And we were talking about how
antagonistic Russians are

00:09:29.690 --> 00:09:31.830
toward capitalism.

00:09:31.830 --> 00:09:35.010
And he said, this is
a big problem.

00:09:35.010 --> 00:09:37.080
Russia just can't embrace
capitalism.

00:09:37.080 --> 00:09:38.510
These people hate it.

00:09:38.510 --> 00:09:42.510
They hate the profit makers
and the financiers.

00:09:42.510 --> 00:09:45.480
And I said to him, well, you
know, it's the same in the

00:09:45.480 --> 00:09:48.320
U.S. How do you know it's
any worse in Russia?

00:09:48.320 --> 00:09:51.950
And so, we decided to do
a questionnaire survey.

00:09:51.950 --> 00:09:54.640
And I was going to read one of
the questions, comparing

00:09:54.640 --> 00:09:58.830
people in Moscow and people in
New York, to see, which one

00:09:58.830 --> 00:10:00.940
understands capitalism better.

00:10:00.940 --> 00:10:04.220
So, one of the questions that
we had was the following --

00:10:04.220 --> 00:10:07.952
We wrote these questions and
translated them into Russian.

00:10:07.952 --> 00:10:10.780
And we tried to make them
exactly the same questions

00:10:10.780 --> 00:10:13.110
between Russian and English.

00:10:13.110 --> 00:10:16.890
So, here's the question we asked
in both cities: ''Grain

00:10:16.890 --> 00:10:20.800
traders in capitalist countries
sometimes hold grain

00:10:20.800 --> 00:10:25.060
without selling it, putting
it in temporary storage in

00:10:25.060 --> 00:10:28.410
anticipation of higher
prices later.

00:10:28.410 --> 00:10:31.790
Do you think this speculation
will cause more frequent

00:10:31.790 --> 00:10:35.920
shortages of flour, bread and
other grain products?

00:10:35.920 --> 00:10:40.450
Or will it cause such shortages
to become rarer?''

00:10:40.450 --> 00:10:42.250
What do you think,
people said?

00:10:42.250 --> 00:10:46.190
Does the process of speculating
in grain cause

00:10:46.190 --> 00:10:48.640
problems or solve problems?

00:10:48.640 --> 00:10:56.000
Well, we found that, in the
USA, 66% said it will make

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:58.990
shortages more common.

00:10:58.990 --> 00:11:03.540
But in the Soviet Union, in
Moscow, only 45% thought it

00:11:03.540 --> 00:11:07.830
would make shortages
more common.

00:11:07.830 --> 00:11:09.670
Both of them were wrong.

00:11:09.670 --> 00:11:12.130
A lot of them were wrong, but
the Russians were better,

00:11:12.130 --> 00:11:14.590
closer to the truth than
the Americans.

00:11:14.590 --> 00:11:18.110
Living in the financial capital
of the USA, most

00:11:18.110 --> 00:11:22.040
people think that speculating in
grain creates problems. But

00:11:22.040 --> 00:11:24.480
wait a minute, what is
speculation in grain?

00:11:24.480 --> 00:11:27.880
That means holding it off,
expecting higher

00:11:27.880 --> 00:11:30.000
prices later, right?

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:32.630
Isn't that what you have
to do if you are

00:11:32.630 --> 00:11:34.920
managing a grain market?

00:11:34.920 --> 00:11:36.870
Now, think of it this way
-- and I'm coming now to

00:11:36.870 --> 00:11:38.610
agricultural futures.

00:11:38.610 --> 00:11:42.020
In the simplest world,
there's one harvest

00:11:42.020 --> 00:11:45.130
of wheat every year.

00:11:45.130 --> 00:11:48.300
And that harvest comes in a
certain time of the year,

00:11:48.300 --> 00:11:50.280
every year.

00:11:50.280 --> 00:11:50.870
Once a year.

00:11:50.870 --> 00:11:55.170
And it has to be held in storage
over the year, right?

00:11:55.170 --> 00:11:57.150
Because people don't
eat it all at once.

00:11:57.150 --> 00:11:59.010
You eat it over the
whole year.

00:11:59.010 --> 00:12:01.390
So, somebody is storing grain.

00:12:01.390 --> 00:12:03.530
This is a fundamental problem.

00:12:03.530 --> 00:12:05.290
That's a business.

00:12:05.290 --> 00:12:08.400
So, you have to know that
somewhere there's some

00:12:08.400 --> 00:12:11.490
warehouse holding the grain that
you will be consuming in

00:12:11.490 --> 00:12:13.210
six months time.

00:12:13.210 --> 00:12:14.930
And that warehouse
is run by some

00:12:14.930 --> 00:12:19.550
professionals who do that.

00:12:19.550 --> 00:12:22.710
If they think prices are higher
later, they'll keep it

00:12:22.710 --> 00:12:24.550
longer in the warehouse.

00:12:24.550 --> 00:12:25.960
And what does that do?

00:12:25.960 --> 00:12:27.840
That evens out the price.

00:12:27.840 --> 00:12:29.440
It doesn't make it worse.

00:12:29.440 --> 00:12:32.570
If they think there's going to
be a shortage of grain, they

00:12:32.570 --> 00:12:35.410
hold it back now and the
price of grain goes up.

00:12:35.410 --> 00:12:37.380
And so, everyone starts
consuming a little less

00:12:37.380 --> 00:12:40.090
because of the higher price, and
it smoothes things out and

00:12:40.090 --> 00:12:41.910
it works better.

00:12:41.910 --> 00:12:45.010
And this is elementary
economics, but it's not

00:12:45.010 --> 00:12:47.050
understood, I think,
by most people.

00:12:49.780 --> 00:12:55.600
And the futures markets are
just sophisticated markets

00:12:55.600 --> 00:12:57.540
that help that process.

00:12:57.540 --> 00:12:59.950
So, I'm going to start with
agricultural futures in

00:12:59.950 --> 00:13:01.070
talking about this.

00:13:01.070 --> 00:13:06.420
And I want to start also with
a very homely -- it's not

00:13:06.420 --> 00:13:08.170
homely -- it's a very elementary
example, because

00:13:08.170 --> 00:13:09.870
it's the first futures market.

00:13:09.870 --> 00:13:11.745
So, where do you think futures
markets started?

00:13:14.700 --> 00:13:18.640
You would think, it started in
New York, or Chicago, or

00:13:18.640 --> 00:13:20.266
London, or Paris.

00:13:20.266 --> 00:13:30.640
It actually started in Japan
in a place called Dojima,

00:13:30.640 --> 00:13:34.400
which is in the city of Osaka.

00:13:34.400 --> 00:13:45.260
And they started in the 1600s.

00:13:45.260 --> 00:13:46.460
So, let's go back.

00:13:46.460 --> 00:13:53.970
If we can go back to the year
1673, in Osaka in Japan.

00:13:53.970 --> 00:13:57.360
Japan was heavily dependent
on rice.

00:13:57.360 --> 00:14:01.900
And the rice farmers would farm
all over Japan, but there

00:14:01.900 --> 00:14:04.950
was a rice market in Dojima,
which was the

00:14:04.950 --> 00:14:06.620
national rice market.

00:14:06.620 --> 00:14:08.260
And I have data here.

00:14:08.260 --> 00:14:12.790
According to a study, there
were 91 rice warehouses in

00:14:12.790 --> 00:14:16.230
Dojima in 1673.

00:14:16.230 --> 00:14:19.950
That's a long time
ago, isn't it?

00:14:19.950 --> 00:14:22.590
So, it was a big storage place
for rice, and they were

00:14:22.590 --> 00:14:23.850
storing it all year.

00:14:23.850 --> 00:14:28.750
And people would come, people
who were merchants for rice,

00:14:28.750 --> 00:14:32.570
and they would come to Dojima
and they would sign contracts

00:14:32.570 --> 00:14:34.270
to get rice.

00:14:34.270 --> 00:14:36.240
I live in some town
20 miles from

00:14:36.240 --> 00:14:38.860
here, I'm a rice merchant.

00:14:38.860 --> 00:14:42.150
I need a regular supply of
rice from your warehouse.

00:14:42.150 --> 00:14:43.230
Can you supply it to me?

00:14:43.230 --> 00:14:45.830
And the guy would give you a
terms, and that would be a

00:14:45.830 --> 00:14:48.550
forward contract.

00:14:48.550 --> 00:14:51.960
And this is what was happening
before the futures market.

00:14:51.960 --> 00:14:55.960
Forward contracts precede
futures contracts.

00:14:55.960 --> 00:14:57.720
So, do you see what it is?

00:14:57.720 --> 00:14:58.590
You're a rice merchant.

00:14:58.590 --> 00:14:59.260
You make a deal.

00:14:59.260 --> 00:15:04.150
You sign a contract that I
will pay you so much in

00:15:04.150 --> 00:15:07.800
currency at every month, and
you'll give me so much rice.

00:15:07.800 --> 00:15:11.100
And you'll deliver it here,
and I'll take it, and I'll

00:15:11.100 --> 00:15:12.350
sell it in my town.

00:15:15.730 --> 00:15:18.830
Problems developed in the
forward market that led to the

00:15:18.830 --> 00:15:21.690
development of a
futures market.

00:15:21.690 --> 00:15:26.450
And the problem is, one of the
problems is that there's

00:15:26.450 --> 00:15:28.530
counterparty risk.

00:15:28.530 --> 00:15:30.050
You are a rice merchant.

00:15:30.050 --> 00:15:32.700
You make a deal with
a warehouse.

00:15:32.700 --> 00:15:36.140
That's one person dealing
with one person, right?

00:15:36.140 --> 00:15:39.570
What if one of the guys
reneges on the deal?

00:15:39.570 --> 00:15:44.600
So, for example, what if the
price of rice falls?

00:15:44.600 --> 00:15:48.660
Then you, the merchant, will
say, I'm not going to go back

00:15:48.660 --> 00:15:50.420
and buy according to this
contract, because

00:15:50.420 --> 00:15:51.910
it's cheaper now.

00:15:51.910 --> 00:15:53.610
I'll buy it somewhere else.

00:15:53.610 --> 00:15:56.370
So, I just don't show up, and
then the warehouse is saying,

00:15:56.370 --> 00:15:58.210
what happened to our contract?

00:15:58.210 --> 00:15:59.490
And you're nowhere
to be found.

00:16:02.020 --> 00:16:04.890
Or if it goes the other way, if
rice goes up, the warehouse

00:16:04.890 --> 00:16:06.250
might renege.

00:16:06.250 --> 00:16:09.900
They'd say, we signed this
contract but there's something

00:16:09.900 --> 00:16:12.460
wrong with it, and we're
not going to honor it.

00:16:12.460 --> 00:16:15.220
So, it messes up.

00:16:15.220 --> 00:16:18.650
It is also possible that one of
the two counterparties is

00:16:18.650 --> 00:16:22.530
just a sociopath or something,
or is an alcoholic, or

00:16:22.530 --> 00:16:24.110
something is wrong.

00:16:24.110 --> 00:16:25.420
So, the market doesn't
work well.

00:16:25.420 --> 00:16:29.500
So, what they invented in
Japan was the first true

00:16:29.500 --> 00:16:31.740
futures market.

00:16:31.740 --> 00:16:36.750
And the market worked like
this: There was a trading

00:16:36.750 --> 00:16:38.840
floor in Dojima.

00:16:38.840 --> 00:16:42.060
And rice traders would come
there, and there were certain

00:16:42.060 --> 00:16:45.750
hours of the day, when you
would trade contracts for

00:16:45.750 --> 00:16:47.710
future delivery.

00:16:47.710 --> 00:16:51.829
But they were standardized
contracts, mediated by the

00:16:51.829 --> 00:16:53.800
exchange, so that there
would be no

00:16:53.800 --> 00:16:56.260
problem with the contract.

00:16:56.260 --> 00:17:02.310
And then every day, there would
be a trading time, and

00:17:02.310 --> 00:17:07.800
you could buy and sell contracts
for future delivery.

00:17:07.800 --> 00:17:11.750
Moreover, they enforced
trading hours.

00:17:11.750 --> 00:17:13.615
And this is something
that's kind of

00:17:13.615 --> 00:17:15.340
an interesting invention.

00:17:15.340 --> 00:17:17.860
They didn't have --

00:17:17.860 --> 00:17:18.840
I guess they didn't
have clocks.

00:17:18.840 --> 00:17:20.050
I don't know what they had.

00:17:20.050 --> 00:17:23.000
But they had a certain time,
when trading would stop, and

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:25.370
they wanted to stop all the
trading at the same time.

00:17:25.370 --> 00:17:26.720
They didn't want people
dribbling out.

00:17:26.720 --> 00:17:28.990
They wanted it to be
a good market.

00:17:28.990 --> 00:17:34.070
So, they would light a fuse, and
it would be a bright light

00:17:34.070 --> 00:17:35.640
in the middle of the
trading floor.

00:17:35.640 --> 00:17:38.550
And you'd see the fuse burning
down, and when it burned out,

00:17:38.550 --> 00:17:40.220
all trading stopped.

00:17:40.220 --> 00:17:42.220
So, they had trading hours.

00:17:42.220 --> 00:17:44.930
Moreover, they had a problem
that some of the traders

00:17:44.930 --> 00:17:46.470
wouldn't stop trading.

00:17:46.470 --> 00:17:49.860
So, this is something that they
did in Dojima, they had

00:17:49.860 --> 00:17:53.910
men called watermen, who came
out with buckets of water.

00:17:53.910 --> 00:17:56.720
And they would throw the buckets
of water on anyone who

00:17:56.720 --> 00:17:58.200
was still trading.

00:17:58.200 --> 00:17:59.250
So that worked.

00:17:59.250 --> 00:18:01.640
It stopped trading.

00:18:01.640 --> 00:18:04.250
They also had hand signals.

00:18:04.250 --> 00:18:04.930
This was big.

00:18:04.930 --> 00:18:05.630
This is big time.

00:18:05.630 --> 00:18:08.130
You were trading rice
for all of Japan.

00:18:08.130 --> 00:18:12.570
And you may think the 16- or
1700s are long ago, but a lot

00:18:12.570 --> 00:18:15.910
of rice was traded and it got
really noisy and difficult.

00:18:15.910 --> 00:18:18.800
They found that it was so many
people trading on the floor,

00:18:18.800 --> 00:18:20.995
that you couldn't hear
anyone talk.

00:18:20.995 --> 00:18:25.990
And there'd be shouting and
it was noisy, and so, they

00:18:25.990 --> 00:18:28.530
devised a system of
hand signals.

00:18:28.530 --> 00:18:32.150
And the Dojima hand signals
were, I don't know exactly,

00:18:32.150 --> 00:18:33.330
but something like this.

00:18:33.330 --> 00:18:35.090
If your hand was out,
you put your hand

00:18:35.090 --> 00:18:36.642
out, that means sell.

00:18:36.642 --> 00:18:39.430
You put your hand this
way, it meant buy.

00:18:39.430 --> 00:18:41.770
And if you put three fingers
up, it means

00:18:41.770 --> 00:18:43.830
selling three contracts.

00:18:43.830 --> 00:18:45.310
That kind of thing.

00:18:45.310 --> 00:18:49.700
I don't know the whole system,
but that's where it started.

00:18:49.700 --> 00:18:53.250
That whole concept was copied
all over the world in

00:18:53.250 --> 00:18:55.210
subsequent centuries.

00:18:55.210 --> 00:18:56.700
So, what is it that happened?

00:18:56.700 --> 00:18:58.790
And the other thing is, what
were the contracts that you

00:18:58.790 --> 00:19:00.540
bought and sold?

00:19:00.540 --> 00:19:03.940
The problem with the forward
market is that the contracts

00:19:03.940 --> 00:19:06.770
are all different.

00:19:06.770 --> 00:19:09.080
One guy made a contract with one
guy, and he said, I want

00:19:09.080 --> 00:19:10.230
my delivery here.

00:19:10.230 --> 00:19:12.820
And I don't like this
kind of rice.

00:19:12.820 --> 00:19:13.820
I want this kind.

00:19:13.820 --> 00:19:17.070
And you better make sure that
there's not a single insect in

00:19:17.070 --> 00:19:18.720
it, or I'm going to reject
the whole thing.

00:19:21.240 --> 00:19:22.180
But that's all different.

00:19:22.180 --> 00:19:25.750
So, you don't know what --

00:19:25.750 --> 00:19:27.380
these contracts, you don't
even know what the

00:19:27.380 --> 00:19:28.660
price of rice is.

00:19:28.660 --> 00:19:34.030
If someone said, I paid
so much to get rice

00:19:34.030 --> 00:19:34.960
in the future --

00:19:34.960 --> 00:19:36.925
but you have to say, well,
under what circumstances?

00:19:36.925 --> 00:19:38.360
And what kind of rice?

00:19:38.360 --> 00:19:39.060
And where?

00:19:39.060 --> 00:19:43.660
And what are the terms
for possible failure?

00:19:43.660 --> 00:19:46.140
You know, there's so many terms
in the contract, so you

00:19:46.140 --> 00:19:48.570
don't even know what the
price of rice is.

00:19:48.570 --> 00:19:50.350
But at the futures market, they

00:19:50.350 --> 00:19:52.620
standardized the contract.

00:19:52.620 --> 00:19:55.390
So, it may not be exactly
what you want, but it's

00:19:55.390 --> 00:19:56.630
standardized.

00:19:56.630 --> 00:19:59.300
So, you deliver rice --

00:19:59.300 --> 00:20:02.800
I don't know all the details
of Dojima, but I'm talking

00:20:02.800 --> 00:20:05.770
about futures markets,
as they evolve.

00:20:05.770 --> 00:20:09.580
In a modern futures market,
agricultural futures market,

00:20:09.580 --> 00:20:11.520
you deliver your --

00:20:11.520 --> 00:20:16.130
the contract is to deliver some
commodity like rice at a

00:20:16.130 --> 00:20:21.230
specified future date, at a
specified future warehouse,

00:20:21.230 --> 00:20:23.470
which would be run
by the exchange.

00:20:23.470 --> 00:20:26.025
And there's inspectors
at the warehouse who

00:20:26.025 --> 00:20:27.930
are expert on grain.

00:20:27.930 --> 00:20:31.740
And they verify, because
they know rice.

00:20:31.740 --> 00:20:32.860
They know it really well.

00:20:32.860 --> 00:20:34.900
And they know that some
rice has bugs in it.

00:20:34.900 --> 00:20:36.215
They know how to find out.

00:20:36.215 --> 00:20:37.470
They have a standard.

00:20:37.470 --> 00:20:40.270
Of course, there can always be
some bugs in it, but they have

00:20:40.270 --> 00:20:42.060
a standard and they have
a way of measuring,

00:20:42.060 --> 00:20:44.520
and they get it right.

00:20:44.520 --> 00:20:48.200
And so, all those contracts
are exactly the same.

00:20:48.200 --> 00:20:55.500
And so, they become the price.

00:20:55.500 --> 00:20:59.190
It turns out, funny thing, the
futures market almost becomes

00:20:59.190 --> 00:21:02.870
the real market, because they're
all standardized.

00:21:02.870 --> 00:21:04.330
The futures price --

00:21:04.330 --> 00:21:05.510
You know where it's delivered.

00:21:05.510 --> 00:21:06.900
You know what's delivered,
exactly.

00:21:10.180 --> 00:21:14.360
The futures market becomes
the market, in a sense.

00:21:14.360 --> 00:21:19.190
The fact that it's in the future
is, in effect, a help,

00:21:19.190 --> 00:21:21.870
because since it's a comfortable
time in the

00:21:21.870 --> 00:21:24.810
future, it's well defined.

00:21:24.810 --> 00:21:26.330
Whereas the spot market --

00:21:26.330 --> 00:21:30.270
the spot market is the market
for rice, or whatever it is,

00:21:30.270 --> 00:21:33.090
today as it's traded.

00:21:33.090 --> 00:21:34.950
The spot market is
inscrutable.

00:21:34.950 --> 00:21:36.590
It's hard to understand.

00:21:36.590 --> 00:21:40.220
So, let's think about a farmer
today, who grows rice, or

00:21:40.220 --> 00:21:42.260
wheat, or soybeans,
or something.

00:21:42.260 --> 00:21:44.740
If you drive through farming
countries, listen to the

00:21:44.740 --> 00:21:47.720
radio, regularly they'll
give prices.

00:21:47.720 --> 00:21:50.960
Soybeans, wheat, rice,
et cetera.

00:21:50.960 --> 00:21:51.910
Why do they give that?

00:21:51.910 --> 00:21:53.020
Because farmers care.

00:21:53.020 --> 00:21:53.940
They're raising this stuff.

00:21:53.940 --> 00:21:56.170
It's their whole livelihood,
whether they make a profit or

00:21:56.170 --> 00:21:57.620
not, depends on it.

00:21:57.620 --> 00:21:59.240
What prices do they quote?

00:21:59.240 --> 00:22:02.200
They quote the futures
prices, even though

00:22:02.200 --> 00:22:03.420
they're in the future.

00:22:03.420 --> 00:22:06.320
But they quote them, because
they mean something and

00:22:06.320 --> 00:22:07.250
they're standardized.

00:22:07.250 --> 00:22:09.810
So, that's why the
futures market

00:22:09.810 --> 00:22:13.630
becomes the central market.

00:22:13.630 --> 00:22:17.240
I want to just say something
about futures --

00:22:17.240 --> 00:22:21.980
Japan started the futures
markets in the 1600s, and they

00:22:21.980 --> 00:22:26.610
were the world leader in rice
futures until 1939.

00:22:26.610 --> 00:22:30.080
And then, at World War II, the
Japanese government shut the

00:22:30.080 --> 00:22:31.790
futures market down.

00:22:31.790 --> 00:22:34.350
And to this day since,
there is no rice

00:22:34.350 --> 00:22:35.900
futures market in Japan.

00:22:35.900 --> 00:22:37.250
Believe it or not.

00:22:37.250 --> 00:22:41.490
The inventors, they're talking
now of starting it up again.

00:22:41.490 --> 00:22:44.030
Where do they trade
rice futures?

00:22:44.030 --> 00:22:47.460
Well, the USA is the main
market, even though you don't

00:22:47.460 --> 00:22:55.300
think of the U.S. as
a market for rice.

00:22:55.300 --> 00:22:57.330
But the point is, that markets
have to be centralized.

00:22:57.330 --> 00:23:00.340
And that people want the
centralized market, and if it

00:23:00.340 --> 00:23:03.330
happens to be in Chicago,
so be it.

