00:43:18.850 --> 00:43:21.980
the equation that defines, when
it is that there's just

00:43:21.980 --> 00:43:25.540
no profit to storing grain.

00:43:25.540 --> 00:43:26.480
There's only a normal
profit, right?

00:43:26.480 --> 00:43:28.720
If people who do it --

00:43:28.720 --> 00:43:30.355
This equation can't
hold exactly.

00:43:30.355 --> 00:43:33.750
Or if it held exactly, then no
one would store grain, but it

00:43:33.750 --> 00:43:36.470
has to be approximately
valuable.

00:43:39.030 --> 00:43:40.700
So, do you see?

00:43:40.700 --> 00:43:43.490
How else do I say this?

00:43:43.490 --> 00:43:46.890
It shows that normally the
futures price is above the

00:43:46.890 --> 00:43:48.450
spot price.

00:43:48.450 --> 00:43:50.580
And as time goes on --

00:43:50.580 --> 00:43:54.250
I don't mean time in this sense,
I mean calendar time --

00:43:54.250 --> 00:43:57.810
the futures price will converge
on the spot price,

00:43:57.810 --> 00:44:01.040
because the interest rate, the
horizon for the interest rate

00:44:01.040 --> 00:44:03.315
and the storage costs --

00:44:03.315 --> 00:44:08.010
this is in percent, and
this is in percent --

00:44:08.010 --> 00:44:08.390
goes down.

00:44:08.390 --> 00:44:10.014
So, let me just clarify that.

00:44:14.080 --> 00:44:17.830
Let's talk about a perfect
world, where there's no

00:44:17.830 --> 00:44:22.190
harvest uncertainty, nothing
happens except the crop is

00:44:22.190 --> 00:44:23.280
normally produced.

00:44:23.280 --> 00:44:25.290
And it's wheat.

00:44:25.290 --> 00:44:26.520
And let's say --

00:44:26.520 --> 00:44:28.540
I'm going to do a plot.

00:44:28.540 --> 00:44:30.390
And this is time.

00:44:30.390 --> 00:44:32.820
This is calendar time,
not maturity time

00:44:32.820 --> 00:44:34.720
like on this plot.

00:44:34.720 --> 00:44:38.330
And this is the price of --

00:44:38.330 --> 00:44:41.550
I'm going to plot the
price of wheat.

00:44:41.550 --> 00:44:44.530
Now, what does wheat
do over the year?

00:44:44.530 --> 00:44:46.470
It has a seasonal pattern.

00:44:46.470 --> 00:44:50.840
I'm going to do an abstract
form of seasonal.

00:44:50.840 --> 00:44:52.700
This is what the price
of wheat does.

00:44:52.700 --> 00:44:53.410
And this is a year.

00:44:53.410 --> 00:44:58.990
This is year 1, this is year
2, this is year 3, year 4.

00:44:58.990 --> 00:45:05.670
This is the price of wheat
in each of these years.

00:45:05.670 --> 00:45:08.510
It falls every harvest
time, right?

00:45:08.510 --> 00:45:11.960
It has to be rising until
harvest, because somebody has

00:45:11.960 --> 00:45:12.910
to be storing grain.

00:45:12.910 --> 00:45:14.430
And the price has to go
up, because they're

00:45:14.430 --> 00:45:16.660
facing storage costs.

00:45:16.660 --> 00:45:23.010
And then, every spring, every
harvest time, it collapses.

00:45:23.010 --> 00:45:24.290
And it does it again
