You can't figure it out.

00:52:11.190 --> 00:52:12.425
There's just too many contracts

00:52:12.425 --> 00:52:14.750
and they're all different.

00:52:14.750 --> 00:52:18.530
There is a spot market for oil,
but that's just overflow.

00:52:18.530 --> 00:52:19.610
You know what happens?

00:52:19.610 --> 00:52:20.800
There'll be some mistake.

00:52:20.800 --> 00:52:26.030
Someone delivered too much oil
to the New Haven harbor, or

00:52:26.030 --> 00:52:29.190
someone reneged on a contract,
now I've got this extra oil.

00:52:29.190 --> 00:52:34.230
It goes on to the spot market,
but that market is tiny and is

00:52:34.230 --> 00:52:36.460
not reliable.

00:52:36.460 --> 00:52:38.030
You don't know what kind of oil
it was, you know, it's all

00:52:38.030 --> 00:52:39.280
different --

00:52:40.860 --> 00:52:42.650
what the issues are.

00:52:42.650 --> 00:52:47.730
So, when you hear oil prices,
you're hearing futures prices.

00:52:47.730 --> 00:52:48.500
So what's happening?

00:52:48.500 --> 00:52:54.260
How can it be that the futures
price in 2015 is lower than

00:52:54.260 --> 00:52:55.500
the price today?

00:52:55.500 --> 00:52:57.180
Well, there is something
funny going on.

00:52:57.180 --> 00:53:00.280
I'll tell you one thing that
it does mean to me, is that

00:53:00.280 --> 00:53:07.130
nobody is planning to store oil
between now and 2015, at

00:53:07.130 --> 00:53:10.060
least not as a storage
business.

00:53:10.060 --> 00:53:12.580
Because I'm going
to lose money.

00:53:12.580 --> 00:53:16.490
I'm going to be selling at less,
unless I have negative

00:53:16.490 --> 00:53:18.380
storage costs.

00:53:18.380 --> 00:53:20.700
I'm not going to store oil
between now and then.

00:53:20.700 --> 00:53:22.290
I'll store it for now.

00:53:22.290 --> 00:53:25.950
So, that means that people are
kind of trying to store a lot

00:53:25.950 --> 00:53:29.040
of it now, because the contango
is there, but it's

00:53:29.040 --> 00:53:31.230
going to end in December, and
then they're going to empty

00:53:31.230 --> 00:53:33.810
their storage tanks.

00:53:33.810 --> 00:53:37.240
That must be what storers
are thinking.

00:53:37.240 --> 00:53:39.060
So, this thing doesn't
always hold.

00:53:39.060 --> 00:53:43.923
This only holds when there's
commodity in storage.

00:53:43.923 --> 00:53:50.380
Or you could say, well, it still
holds even when you have

00:53:50.380 --> 00:53:54.930
backwardation, because, in some
sense, storage costs can

00:53:54.930 --> 00:53:57.030
get negative.

00:53:57.030 --> 00:53:59.930
And so let me just talk about,
there's a term that they use

00:53:59.930 --> 00:54:01.240
called convenience yield.

00:54:07.590 --> 00:54:12.420
When the futures curve is in
backwardation, somebody is

00:54:12.420 --> 00:54:14.650
still going to be storing oil.

00:54:14.650 --> 00:54:19.050
So, suppose I have a factory,
and my factory depends on oil,

00:54:19.050 --> 00:54:24.380
because I use it to burn, to
produce whatever we make.

00:54:24.380 --> 00:54:26.845
Am I going to let my warehouse,
my storage tank of

00:54:26.845 --> 00:54:28.380
oil go dry?

00:54:28.380 --> 00:54:33.990
No, I'm going to need some,
just because we might need

00:54:33.990 --> 00:54:35.240
more than we think.

00:54:35.240 --> 00:54:37.110
We might have a buffer stock.

00:54:37.110 --> 00:54:40.320
So, that means, I actually have
negative storage costs.

00:54:40.320 --> 00:54:41.570
I always want oil.

00:54:41.570 --> 00:54:44.180
I don't want ever to let
my tanks go dry.

00:54:44.180 --> 00:54:48.040
So, the only people who are
storing oil, when you have a

00:54:48.040 --> 00:54:52.920
backwardated futures market,
are the people who want

00:54:52.920 --> 00:54:53.810
convenience yield.

00:54:53.810 --> 00:54:55.660
Now, I'm omitting some
subtleties here.

00:54:55.660 --> 00:54:58.910
I'm sorry, but I'm trying to
make the basic point, that

00:54:58.910 --> 00:55:03.050
this equation holds
when the commodity

00:55:03.050 --> 00:55:05.070
underlying is in storage.

00:55:05.070 --> 00:55:08.380
But it doesn't always hold.

