Remember that?

00:57:27.410 --> 00:57:29.460
And the government eventually
busted up

00:57:29.460 --> 00:57:32.200
Standard Oil as a monopoly.

00:57:32.200 --> 00:57:35.420
So, they were starting to
get concerned about oil.

00:57:35.420 --> 00:57:38.230
But then, if you go forward in
time, you see this interesting

00:57:38.230 --> 00:57:38.810
pattern here.

00:57:38.810 --> 00:57:40.590
What was going on here?

00:57:40.590 --> 00:57:48.390
The price of oil became very
stable, until, bang, there was

00:57:48.390 --> 00:57:52.610
this huge upswing in oil.

00:57:52.610 --> 00:57:55.150
Well, what was happening in
this interval of time?

00:57:57.800 --> 00:58:02.650
In the '40s to 60's, the U.S.
was a big producer of oil.

00:58:02.650 --> 00:58:06.280
It kind of got started here, oil
production, with Drake's

00:58:06.280 --> 00:58:10.190
invention of the oil rig.

00:58:10.190 --> 00:58:13.970
And the U.S. was the biggest
producer of oil.

00:58:13.970 --> 00:58:17.790
And during this period, when you
see oil prices were very

00:58:17.790 --> 00:58:24.720
stable, the oil prices were
actually stabilized by the --

00:58:24.720 --> 00:58:26.380
it was produced mostly
in Texas --

00:58:26.380 --> 00:58:29.550
Texas Railroad Commission.

00:58:29.550 --> 00:58:35.350
It says railroad, but it was a
government agency in the state

00:58:35.350 --> 00:58:40.970
of Texas, which worked to
stabilize oil prices.

00:58:40.970 --> 00:58:43.920
But during this period of time,
the U.S. was depleting

00:58:43.920 --> 00:58:48.660
its oil, and other oil
discoveries were coming in.

00:58:48.660 --> 00:58:51.370
And so, this whole period --
this is before there were any

00:58:51.370 --> 00:58:53.130
futures markets, because
there was no reason

00:58:53.130 --> 00:58:54.740
for a futures market.

00:58:54.740 --> 00:58:57.430
Oil prices were very stable.

00:58:57.430 --> 00:59:02.060
And then, you see, here, a
sudden jump up in oil prices.

00:59:02.060 --> 00:59:08.230
And this point right here is
called the first oil crisis.

00:59:08.230 --> 00:59:14.340
So, the first oil crisis, it
kind of stands out on a

00:59:14.340 --> 00:59:15.190
diagram, right?

00:59:15.190 --> 00:59:18.430
Looking at the whole history,
if you exclude those early

00:59:18.430 --> 00:59:22.600
fluctuations in oil that you see
in the 1870s, which were

00:59:22.600 --> 00:59:25.550
not really so important, because
people were really so

00:59:25.550 --> 00:59:28.880
dependent on oil.

00:59:28.880 --> 00:59:41.580
So, the first oil crisis
was 1973 to '74.

00:59:41.580 --> 00:59:46.650
And this prompted the creation
of the futures market.

00:59:46.650 --> 00:59:49.570
Because what happened was --

00:59:49.570 --> 00:59:54.040
it was actually coincided with
the Yom Kippur War in Israel.

00:59:54.040 --> 01:00:05.000
And it was created by a blockade
against oil in

01:00:05.000 --> 01:00:06.050
oil-producing countries.

01:00:06.050 --> 01:00:08.330
The U.S. was no longer,
by this time, the

01:00:08.330 --> 01:00:10.480
major producer of oil.

01:00:10.480 --> 01:00:15.220
We had something called OPEC,
which is the Organization of

01:00:15.220 --> 01:00:18.855
Petroleum Exporting Countries.

01:00:18.855 --> 01:00:26.880
It actually goes back
to 1961 with Qatar.

01:00:26.880 --> 01:00:36.650
1962, Libya, Indonesia.

01:00:36.650 --> 01:00:41.440
And then, we added the Abu Dhabi
in '67, the United Arab

01:00:41.440 --> 01:00:48.490
Emirates, '74, Algeria in 1969,
Nigeria in 1971, Ecuador

01:00:48.490 --> 01:00:52.550
in 1973, Gabon in 1975.

01:00:52.550 --> 01:00:55.440
So what happened was, although
the U.S. broke the Standard

01:00:55.440 --> 01:01:02.050
Oil monopoly around the turn of
the century, a new monopoly

01:01:02.050 --> 01:01:04.800
developed, and it was outside
the U.S. And so, there was no

01:01:04.800 --> 01:01:11.010
trustbusters to break
this monopoly.

01:01:11.010 --> 01:01:15.660
And so, what happened was, the
oil exporting countries who

01:01:15.660 --> 01:01:23.270
belonged to OPEC, who wanted
to use oil prices as a

01:01:23.270 --> 01:01:28.490
strategy to deal with Israel,
they restricted

01:01:28.490 --> 01:01:29.700
their supply of oil.

01:01:29.700 --> 01:01:34.660
And it caused the first
oil crisis right here.

01:01:34.660 --> 01:01:40.050
I was going to mention another
historical fact that, I think,

01:01:40.050 --> 01:01:44.500
precedes this, but it's
part of the story.

01:01:44.500 --> 01:01:53.535
And that is nationalizations
of oil.

01:02:00.560 --> 01:02:03.910
It used to be that big oil
companies went around the

01:02:03.910 --> 01:02:06.750
world and found oil deposits.

01:02:06.750 --> 01:02:08.660
And then, they would buy the
land, and they wouldn't tell

01:02:08.660 --> 01:02:10.290
anybody what they were doing.

01:02:10.290 --> 01:02:14.380
They'd buy the land that
had the oil under it.

01:02:14.380 --> 01:02:16.800
So, the oil companies
were very rich.

01:02:16.800 --> 01:02:20.990
But there was discontent in the
less developed countries,

01:02:20.990 --> 01:02:23.060
who sold them the land and
thought, why did we

01:02:23.060 --> 01:02:25.070
get gypped like that?

01:02:25.070 --> 01:02:28.740
And so, they started
a process.

01:02:28.740 --> 01:02:35.170
It started with Mexico
in 1938.

01:02:35.170 --> 01:02:40.560
So, oil used to be owned
by the oil companies.

01:02:40.560 --> 01:02:43.430
Mexico said, no,
not any longer.

01:02:43.430 --> 01:02:45.480
It's our national heritage.

01:02:45.480 --> 01:02:47.600
We never should have
sold it to you.

01:02:47.600 --> 01:02:49.410
We're just taking it back.

01:02:49.410 --> 01:02:52.120
This was considered outrageous
at the time.

01:02:52.120 --> 01:02:55.220
No country should violate
property rights like that.

01:02:55.220 --> 01:02:58.605
But it was kind of
a leftist --

01:02:58.605 --> 01:03:01.480
the word nationalization
was a new word.

01:03:01.480 --> 01:03:06.560
It was kind of like the people
expressing their heritage.

01:03:06.560 --> 01:03:08.110
It started to take.

01:03:08.110 --> 01:03:14.670
Then, Iran in 1951.

01:03:14.670 --> 01:03:16.740
And then, other countries
followed.

01:03:16.740 --> 01:03:20.200
So, oil got taken away from
international companies and

01:03:20.200 --> 01:03:24.100
put under government control of
less developed countries.

01:03:24.100 --> 01:03:27.380
And then, there was a monopoly
called OPEC, and that produced

01:03:27.380 --> 01:03:30.040
this crisis right here.

01:03:30.040 --> 01:03:36.260
There was a second oil
crisis in 1979-80.

01:03:36.260 --> 01:03:40.760
And this one, again, was
associated with trouble in the

01:03:40.760 --> 01:03:49.770
Middle East. So, in '79-80, we
had the Iranian revolution,

01:03:49.770 --> 01:03:52.740
which again disrupted
oil supply.

01:03:52.740 --> 01:03:57.830
So, 1979-80 is the second
oil crisis.

01:04:01.260 --> 01:04:05.210
And that is due to the fall of
the Shah of Iran, and the

01:04:05.210 --> 01:04:08.080
arrival of the Ayatollah
Khomeini, and

01:04:08.080 --> 01:04:11.080
the Iran-Iraq War.

01:04:11.080 --> 01:04:14.710
And so, you can see the huge
increase in oil prices.

01:04:14.710 --> 01:04:17.500
These were real panic situations
at the time,

01:04:17.500 --> 01:04:20.360
because people were not
used to these --

01:04:20.360 --> 01:04:23.310
people were used to the stable
oil prices, and it was just

01:04:23.310 --> 01:04:25.200
something taken for granted.

01:04:25.200 --> 01:04:28.397
But this put the world in a
state of shock, because oil

01:04:28.397 --> 01:04:35.240
prices really jumped up almost
sixfold, about sixfold, in a

01:04:35.240 --> 01:04:36.490
matter of --

01:04:38.910 --> 01:04:40.110
how many years is that? --

01:04:40.110 --> 01:04:41.360
six, seven years.

01:04:43.920 --> 01:04:50.200
So, this left a lot of interest
and enthusiasm for

01:04:50.200 --> 01:04:53.090
oil futures, and it became a
major market of the kind we

01:04:53.090 --> 01:04:54.460
know about today.

01:04:54.460 --> 01:04:55.826
You know, what happened here?

01:04:55.826 --> 01:04:57.050
This mark.

01:04:57.050 --> 01:04:58.170
This is another --

01:04:58.170 --> 01:05:04.100
This is the second Iraq War,
when Saddam Hussein was

01:05:04.100 --> 01:05:06.705
overthrown.

01:05:06.705 --> 01:05:08.510
And the U.S. and
other countries

01:05:08.510 --> 01:05:10.170
were involved in that.

01:05:10.170 --> 01:05:13.880
But what it did is, it cut off
the supply of oil briefly,

01:05:13.880 --> 01:05:17.560
because the Persian Gulf was
shut down because of a war.

01:05:17.560 --> 01:05:20.240
You can bet that the futures
market was heavily

01:05:20.240 --> 01:05:22.480
backwardated right
then, for oil.

01:05:22.480 --> 01:05:26.680
Because everyone knew that the
oil prices were not --

01:05:26.680 --> 01:05:30.850
we weren't running out of oil,
we couldn't get at it because

01:05:30.850 --> 01:05:32.430
of the war.

01:05:32.430 --> 01:05:36.500
And so, this was another
oil-induced spike.

01:05:36.500 --> 01:05:39.830
Every one of these spikes
produced a major worldwide

01:05:39.830 --> 01:05:42.760
recession, because the world
wasn't ready for

01:05:42.760 --> 01:05:43.600
these spikes enough.

01:05:43.600 --> 01:05:47.720
So, we see this huge spike
in oil in '73,

01:05:47.720 --> 01:05:49.490
and a worldwide recession.

01:05:49.490 --> 01:05:51.880
Again, another worldwide
recession.

01:05:51.880 --> 01:05:54.970
This one was called The Great
Recession, people forgot that

01:05:54.970 --> 01:05:56.580
they called it that,
and they use that

01:05:56.580 --> 01:05:59.070
term again more recently.

01:05:59.070 --> 01:06:00.700
And then there was another
worldwide recession --

01:06:00.700 --> 01:06:03.020
every one of these did it.

01:06:03.020 --> 01:06:06.500
And so, you can see the
fundamental importance of oil,

01:06:06.500 --> 01:06:08.910
and of oil futures, because
oil futures is

01:06:08.910 --> 01:06:10.560
managing the risk.

01:06:10.560 --> 01:06:15.200
If you bought an oil futures
contract, you

01:06:15.200 --> 01:06:17.050
weren't impacted by this.

01:06:17.050 --> 01:06:22.290
If you bought a contract just
before this, then the oil

01:06:22.290 --> 01:06:23.620
crisis doesn't mean
anything to me.

01:06:23.620 --> 01:06:26.170
It's not my problem, because
I've already

01:06:26.170 --> 01:06:27.670
locked in my price.

01:06:27.670 --> 01:06:30.540
And it's really safe, because
the way the futures markets

01:06:30.540 --> 01:06:34.000
work, they've got this daily
settlement process.

01:06:34.000 --> 01:06:35.340
So, you don't have to
worry about your

01:06:35.340 --> 01:06:37.070
counterparty reneging.

01:06:37.070 --> 01:06:39.150
It's very civilized.

01:06:39.150 --> 01:06:41.710
It's a tough world out there,
where they're fighting wars,

01:06:41.710 --> 01:06:44.360
but in Chicago, where the
futures markets are --

01:06:44.360 --> 01:06:46.690
or it was in New York
back then --

01:06:46.690 --> 01:06:49.790
it's a very civilized market.

01:06:49.790 --> 01:06:52.210
And so, look here, we have
the latest spike.

01:06:55.980 --> 01:06:57.350
It's even bigger.

01:06:57.350 --> 01:06:58.660
So, oil got to --

01:06:58.660 --> 01:07:00.670
I can't even reach up there --

01:07:00.670 --> 01:07:05.490
oil got up to over $140
a barrel in 2008.

01:07:05.490 --> 01:07:06.815
That's just a short time ago.

01:07:06.815 --> 01:07:08.065
Now, what did that?

01:07:10.750 --> 01:07:14.040
That is kind of a puzzle.

01:07:14.040 --> 01:07:16.830
It has something to do with the
world financial crisis.

01:07:19.500 --> 01:07:23.640
But it's not as well understood
as a reaction to

01:07:23.640 --> 01:07:26.220
any military situation.

01:07:26.220 --> 01:07:28.990
So, it seems like there's
some speculative

01:07:28.990 --> 01:07:31.230
element that took place.

01:07:31.230 --> 01:07:35.040
See ultimately, oil is stored in
the ground, and it's owned

01:07:35.040 --> 01:07:37.690
by people, and they have to
decide how to develop it and

01:07:37.690 --> 01:07:41.590
how fast to produce
it and sell it.

01:07:41.590 --> 01:07:45.210
And there were some quick
changes of thinking around

01:07:45.210 --> 01:07:49.290
then, that surprised
everyone, I think.

01:07:49.290 --> 01:07:53.390
And oil is, again, up above
$100 a barrel right now.

01:07:53.390 --> 01:07:55.860
Just we saw in the
futures curve.

01:07:55.860 --> 01:08:00.899
So, actually the futures curve
that we saw would look kind of

01:08:00.899 --> 01:08:03.200
unimpressive on this
diagram, right?

01:08:03.200 --> 01:08:07.670
It would be just going up a
little more and a little down,

01:08:07.670 --> 01:08:09.755
not big swings that
are predicted.

01:08:19.600 --> 01:08:22.370
I just want to finally conclude
with financial

01:08:22.370 --> 01:08:26.080
futures, which I didn't
emphasize in this lecture.

01:08:26.080 --> 01:08:31.130
But we also have futures
markets in financial

01:08:31.130 --> 01:08:32.580
commodities, and I'm just
going to tell you

01:08:32.580 --> 01:08:34.040
about one of them.

01:08:34.040 --> 01:08:43.530
It's called the S&amp;P 500 futures
market, index futures.

01:08:43.530 --> 01:08:51.370
And now, in effect, you have to
deliver not oil, or rice,

01:08:51.370 --> 01:08:56.600
or wheat, but you have to
deliver the S&amp;P 500 index.

01:08:56.600 --> 01:08:58.229
How do you do that,
by the way?

01:08:58.229 --> 01:09:00.830
How do I deliver 500 stocks?

01:09:00.830 --> 01:09:04.880
Well, there's a procedure, and
it's called cash settlement.

01:09:04.880 --> 01:09:06.300
It's different.

01:09:06.300 --> 01:09:09.029
Instead of showing up at
warehouse with your trucks

01:09:09.029 --> 01:09:14.290
full of wheat, you only show
up with the money, because

01:09:14.290 --> 01:09:18.420
they don't expect you to
do that with stocks.

01:09:21.520 --> 01:09:24.609
What is the storage
cost for stocks?

01:09:24.609 --> 01:09:27.383
Well, you know, it's
actually negative.

01:09:27.383 --> 01:09:29.330
It doesn't cost me
anything to buy.

01:09:29.330 --> 01:09:32.790
If I buy a share in a company
and store it, it

01:09:32.790 --> 01:09:33.550
doesn't cost --

01:09:33.550 --> 01:09:37.149
it's a negative cost, because
they pay a dividend.

01:09:37.149 --> 01:09:40.370
So, the fair value, and this is
what you'll see quoted all

01:09:40.370 --> 01:09:45.500
the time on CNBC, or any
of these business --

01:09:45.500 --> 01:09:46.250
Bloomberg --

01:09:46.250 --> 01:09:49.620
these business networks is --

01:09:52.980 --> 01:10:01.610
So, the futures price is equal
to 1 plus r minus y, times the

01:10:01.610 --> 01:10:03.850
spot price.

01:10:03.850 --> 01:10:07.000
Same formula.

01:10:07.000 --> 01:10:08.270
This is the interest rate.

01:10:12.250 --> 01:10:14.110
And this is the dividend
yield.

01:10:19.220 --> 01:10:23.310
So now, whether the futures
price is above or below the

01:10:23.310 --> 01:10:27.070
spot price, is less clear here,
because it depends on

01:10:27.070 --> 01:10:30.100
whether the interest rate
is higher than the

01:10:30.100 --> 01:10:31.940
dividend rate or lower.

01:10:31.940 --> 01:10:35.600
At this point in history, for
short time horizons, the

01:10:35.600 --> 01:10:38.290
interest rate is less than
the dividend rate.

01:10:38.290 --> 01:10:42.080
We have about a 2% dividend
yield on stocks, and we have

01:10:42.080 --> 01:10:44.560
essentially a 0%
interest rate.

01:10:44.560 --> 01:10:48.440
So, for short horizons, we'd
expect to see the futures

01:10:48.440 --> 01:10:52.200
price less than the spot price
in stock index futures.

01:10:52.200 --> 01:10:55.400
But at longer horizons, I think
that would be reversed.

01:10:55.400 --> 01:10:57.740
But this market is very clear.

01:10:57.740 --> 01:11:01.500
The fair value relationship is
highly predictive of futures

01:11:01.500 --> 01:11:05.460
prices in the S&amp;P 500 index
futures, because there's

01:11:05.460 --> 01:11:07.250
always storage of stocks.

01:11:07.250 --> 01:11:10.640
We never deplete the warehouses
of stocks, so

01:11:10.640 --> 01:11:12.180
they're always there.

01:11:12.180 --> 01:11:14.860
And so, that means that the
futures curve is less

01:11:14.860 --> 01:11:18.980
interesting for stocks
than it is for oil.

01:11:18.980 --> 01:11:22.220
All it does is reflect
fair value.

01:11:22.220 --> 01:11:27.130
And so, it's not like oil, where
the storage situation is

01:11:27.130 --> 01:11:31.520
very complicated, and it's
constantly changing.

01:11:31.520 --> 01:11:38.420
So in a sense, the S&amp;P 500 index
futures is not so much

01:11:38.420 --> 01:11:41.820
about the future.

01:11:41.820 --> 01:11:44.070
The futures curve is not so much
about the future of the

01:11:44.070 --> 01:11:45.290
stock market.

01:11:45.290 --> 01:11:49.160
So, don't make the mistake of
looking at the futures curve

01:11:49.160 --> 01:11:52.420
for the S&amp;P 500, and thinking
I'm going to forecast the

01:11:52.420 --> 01:11:54.210
market using this curve.

01:11:54.210 --> 01:11:56.150
You can't.

01:11:56.150 --> 01:12:00.810
Basically, the S&amp;P 500 is very
hard to forecast. And the

01:12:00.810 --> 01:12:03.960
futures curve doesn't do you
anything, because all it

01:12:03.960 --> 01:12:05.580
reflects is fair value.

01:12:05.580 --> 01:12:09.130
So, some futures markets, like
gold futures is like this

01:12:09.130 --> 01:12:12.880
also, there's always gold in
storage, it never gets

01:12:12.880 --> 01:12:14.190
depleted to zero.

01:12:14.190 --> 01:12:17.440
It's always being stored, so the
gold futures curve is not

01:12:17.440 --> 01:12:18.690
so interesting, either.

